                                    <watches>4</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="145182" author="mhanafi" created="Thu, 10 Mar 2016 20:13:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Please close this issue. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="126511" author="niu" created="Sun, 6 Sep 2015 04:19:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The quota slaves will stop allocating/releasing quot limits from/to master once the quota isn&apos;t enforced (otherwise, that&apos;ll be an unnecessary overhead), so only quota accounting (kbytes &amp;amp; files displayed in lfs quota output) information is still getting updated properly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Mahmoud, I was wondering if you could explain this to customer?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="126053" author="mhanafi" created="Wed, 2 Sep 2015 16:48:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think the issue here is that once enforcement is and then turned off.  When users delete files allocations are not released. So users who have been over their soft quota will show as having over quota and grace time. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know that enforcement is off so it doesn&apos;t matter that they are over their soft quota but users complain that why lfs quota shows them as being over when they are not.&lt;/p&gt;



</comment>
                            <comment id="125973" author="niu" created="Wed, 2 Sep 2015 01:46:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Mahmoud, turn off quota enforcement won&apos;t trigger releasing the allocated limit, it&apos;ll be released when you set the limit to zero.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="125932" author="pjones" created="Tue, 1 Sep 2015 19:07:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Niu&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Could you please advise?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Peter&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
